05416nam a22009495i 9780520932326DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20062006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209323267 a10.1525/97805209323262doi  a(DE-B1597)520117  a(OCoLC)64394494  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1993.5.U6bB656 2006eb 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.430973222  aAP 449832rvk1 aBordwell, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Way Hollywood Tells It :bStory and Style in Modern Movies /cDavid Bordwell. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (309 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Beyond The Blockbuster -- tPart I: A Real Story -- t1. Continuing Tradition, By Any Means Necessary -- t2. Pushing the Premises -- t3. Subjective Stories and Network Narratives -- t4. A Certain Amount of Plot: Tentpoles, Locomotives, Blockbusters, Megapictures, and the Action Movie -- tPart II: A Stylish Style -- t1. Intensified Continuity: Four Dimensions -- t2. Some Likely Sources -- t3. Style, Plain and Fancy -- t4. What’s Missing? -- tAppendix: A Hollywood Timeline, 1960–2004 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHollywood moviemaking is one of the constants of American life, but how much has it changed since the glory days of the big studios? David Bordwell argues that the principles of visual storytelling created in the studio era are alive and well, even in today’s bloated blockbusters. American filmmakers have created a durable tradition—one that we should not be ashamed to call artistic, and one that survives in both mainstream entertainment and niche-marketed indie cinema. Bordwell traces the continuity of this tradition in a wide array of films made since 1960, from romantic comedies like Jerry Maguire and Love Actually to more imposing efforts like A Beautiful Mind. He also draws upon testimony from writers, directors, and editors who are acutely conscious of employing proven principles of plot and visual style. Within the limits of the "classical" approach, innovation can flourish. Bordwell examines how imaginative filmmakers have pushed the premises of the system in films such as JFK, Memento, and Magnolia. He discusses generational, technological, and economic factors leading to stability and change in Hollywood cinema and includes close analyses of selected shots and sequences. As it ranges across four decades, examining classics like American Graffiti and The Godfather as well as recent success like The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers, this book provides a vivid and engaging interpretation of how Hollywood moviemakers have created a vigorous, resourceful tradition of cinematic storytelling that continues to engage audiences around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picture industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion picture industryzUnited States. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aamerican art.  aamerican culture.  aamerican film.  aamerican history.  aamerican life.  aartistic.  ablockbusters.  acinema studies.  acinematic.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  afilm history.  afilm studies.  afilmmaker.  afilmmaking.  ahollywood.  aindie cinema.  aindie movies.  amovie director.  amovie editing.  amovie genres.  amovie studio.  amoviemakers.  amoviemaking.  aromantic comedies.  asocial history.  asocial studies.  astorytelling.  avisual arts.